[36m(TaskRunner pid=197332)[0m 2. **Find the values of \( x \) that make the denominator zero**: Set the factored denominator equal to zero and solve for \( x \).
[36m(TaskRunner pid=197332)[0m    \[
[36m(TaskRunner pid=197332)[0m    (x + 3)(x - 2) = 0
[36m(TaskRunner pid=197332)[0m    \]
[36m(TaskRunner pid=197332)[0m    This gives us two solutions:
[36m(TaskRunner pid=197332)[0m    \[
[36m(TaskRunner pid=197332)[0m    x + 3 = 0 \implies x = -3
[36m(TaskRunner pid=197332)[0m    \]
[36m(TaskRunner pid=197332)[0m    \[
[36m(TaskRunner pid=197332)[0m    x - 2 = 0 \implies x = 2
[36m(TaskRunner pid=197332)[0m    \]
[36m(TaskRunner pid=197332)[0m 
[36m(TaskRunner pid=197332)[0m 3. **Determine the vertical asymptotes**: The function will have vertical asymptotes at \( x = -3 \) and \( x = 2 \), provided that these values do not also make the numerator zero. Since the numerator is 2, which is never zero, the function has vertical asymptotes at both \( x = -3 \) and \( x = 2 \).
[36m(TaskRunner pid=197332)[0m 
